<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1440,1538,1594]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,344,1538,1562]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from Latin and refers to the elytral color pattern, which can be described as pale with two broad, dark bands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[192,1441,1634,1690]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,349,1634,1658]" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Comments.</emphasis>
This genus is endemic to the West Indies. All previously described species are from 
<collectingCountry box="[1368,1435,1634,1658]" name="Cuba" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Cuba</collectingCountry>
, Hispaniola, or 
<collectingCountry box="[371,476,1666,1690]" name="Jamaica" pageId="18" pageNumber="17">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
